President Biden welcomed the Prime Minister of Japan and the President of the Republic of Korea to Camp David for the first-ever standalone summit between the three nations. He emphasized the importance of strengthening the ties between their democracies and how it contributes to a safer world. President Biden thanked both leaders for their political courage and expressed his gratitude for their leadership. President Yoon of Korea highlighted the need for tighter solidarity among the three nations to protect their freedoms and address regional security challenges. Prime Minister Kishida of Japan expressed his condolences for the wildfires in Hawaii and the passing of President Yoon's father. He emphasized the turning point in history and the potential for trilateral strategic collaboration, particularly in response to North Korea and areas such as economic security and supply chains resilience. The leaders looked forward to engaging in frank discussions to declare a new era of partnership. The press was then asked to leave the meeting.